================================================================================
Third-party components
================================================================================

CrumbVMS bundles or depends on the following third-party software. Their own
licenses govern those components; this NOTICE is informational.

-- Bundled / distributed with CrumbVMS --

* mpv / libmpv  (https://mpv.io)
  Used by the desktop client for hardware-accelerated video playback, loaded at
  runtime via libmpv. Stock mpv builds are licensed GPL-2.0-or-later (an mpv
  built with `-Dgpl=false` is LGPL-2.1-or-later). CrumbVMS is AGPL-3.0, which is
  compatible with GPL. When the desktop client is distributed with a bundled
  `libmpv-2.dll`, that mpv build's source and license obligations apply.
  Corresponding source: https://github.com/mpv-player/mpv

* FFmpeg  (https://ffmpeg.org)
  Invoked as a separate subprocess (never linked) by the recorder and by the
  API's export/clip pipelines. The FFmpeg shipped in CrumbVMS's Docker images is
  jellyfin-ffmpeg (a GPL build that enables libx264 etc.), installed from the
  Jellyfin apt repository. Corresponding source:
  https://github.com/jellyfin/jellyfin-ffmpeg (which packages upstream FFmpeg,
  https://git.ffmpeg.org / https://ffmpeg.org).

  Written offer: in accordance with the GNU GPL, the complete corresponding
  source for the exact mpv and FFmpeg builds distributed with CrumbVMS is available
  at the URLs above. If you cannot obtain it there, you may request it from the
  maintainer via the project's GitHub repository and it will be provided.

-- Separate services (run as their own processes; not linked into CrumbVMS) --

* go2rtc  (MIT) , stream restreaming/WebRTC.  https://github.com/AlexxIT/go2rtc
* Frigate (MIT) , optional, bring-your-own object detection over MQTT.
                   https://github.com/blakeblackshear/frigate
* PostgreSQL (PostgreSQL License), the database.  https://www.postgresql.org
* Eclipse Mosquitto (EPL/EDL), optional MQTT broker.  https://mosquitto.org

-- Application dependencies --

The Rust backend (axum, tokio, tower-http, sqlx/tokio-postgres, jsonwebtoken,
argon2, and others), the Android client (AndroidX, Jetpack Compose, Media3,
Retrofit, OkHttp, Coil), the iOS client (Apple frameworks; WebRTC under BSD-3),
and the desktop client (Flutter under BSD-3-Clause; media_kit and
flutter_rust_bridge under MIT/Apache-2.0) are all licensed under permissive
terms (MIT / Apache-2.0 / BSD). See each project's Cargo.toml,
build.gradle.kts, pubspec.yaml, and Swift package manifests for the
authoritative dependency lists.

The optional crumb-alpr worker (services/alpr-worker, opt-in `alpr` compose
profile) builds on the fast-alpr wrappers (MIT) and ONNX Runtime (MIT). Its
default detector weights are YOLOv9-derived models licensed GPL-3.0-or-later
(compatible with AGPL-3.0); they are downloaded by the worker at first run and
are never redistributed by CrumbVMS.

